                <Paragraph>
                    The <strong>Eiffel Tower</strong> (<IPAOption Language="French" Text="Tour Eiffel" IPA="tuʁ‿ɛfɛl" />) is a
                    wrought-iron lattice
                    tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris, France. It is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel,
                    whose
                    company designed and built the tower.
                </Paragraph>

                <Paragraph Title="Design and construction">
                    Constructed from 1887 to 1889 as the entrance to the 1889 World's Fair, it was initially
                    criticized by
                    some of France's leading artists and intellectuals for its design, but it has become a
                    global cultural
                    icon of France and one of the most recognisable structures in the world.
                </Paragraph>

                <Paragraph Title="Table">
                    The Eiffel Tower is made of iron and weighs around 10,000 tonnes. It stands at a height of
                    330 meters
                    and was the tallest man-made structure in the world until the completion of the Chrysler
                    Building in New
                    York in 1930.
